<p><p>40 The following statement from Hobbes regarding the need to understand the overall design applies equally to Bacon: ‘For it is not the bare Words, but the Scope of the writer that giveth the true light, by which any writing is to bee interpreted; and they that insist upon single Texts, without considering the main Designe, can derive nothing from them cleerly’. Hobbes, Thomas, Leviathan, 3 vols. (ed. Malcolm, N.), Oxford: Clarendon Press, 2012, vol. 3, p. 954<a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Leviathan&amp;publication+year=2012&amp;author=Hobbes+Thomas&amp;author=Malcolm+N."><span style="color: #000080; text-decoration:  underline; "> Google Scholar</a>; quoted in Odzuck, Eva Helene, ‘“I professed to write not all to all”: diversified communication in Thomas Hobbes's political philosophy’, Hobbes Studies (2017), 30, pp. 123–155<a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1163/18750257-03002001"><span style="color: #000080; text-decoration:  underline; "> CrossRef</a> | <a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=“I+professed+to+write+not+all+to+all”:+diversified+communication+in+Thomas+Hobbes's+political+philosophy&amp;publication+year=2017&amp;author=Odzuck+Eva+Helene&amp;journal=Hobbes+Studies&amp;volume=30&amp;doi=10.1163/18750257-03002001&amp;pages=123-155"><span style="color: #000080; text-decoration:  underline; ">Google Scholar</a>, 128.</p></p>
